\begin_layout Subsection
Optimal Stopping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose an asset (stock, commodities, real estate) is such that its price
 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 on the open market varies according to a stochastic differential equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{dX_{t}}{dt} & = & X_{t}\left(r+\alpha\right)X_{t}\cdot\text{"noise"}\\
 & = & X_{t}\left(r+\alpha\cdot\text{"noise"}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r,\alpha$
\end_inset

 are known constants and the discount rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is also a known constant (present value of future cash flows - money today
 is worth more than money tomorrow because of inflation and etc.).
 Given that you know 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{s}$
\end_inset

 up to present time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and taking into consideration that the rate of change is noisey, at what
 time should you sell this asset? Since noisey we can only hope for optimal
 stopping strategy that maximizes expected returns (when inflation is taken
 into account).
 Can be solved by solving a corresponding semielliptic second order PDE
 with Dirichlet boundary conditions (function is specified on boundary,
 as opposed to derivatives specified on boundary [Von Neumann bvp])
\end_layout

