\begin_layout Subsection
Options Pricing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose at some time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 the person in problem 4 is offered the right (without obligation) to buy
 one unit of the risky asset at a specified price 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 at a specified future date 
\begin_inset Formula $t=T$
\end_inset

.
 Such a right/asset is called a 
\emph on
European call option
\emph default
.
 How much should they be willing to pay for the option? Problem solved by
 Fischer Black and Myron Scholes - called the Black-Scholes equation for
 option pricing
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial V}{\partial t}+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}S^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}V}{\partial S^{2}}+rS\frac{\partial V}{\partial S}-rV=0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the price of the option as a function of the price of the asset, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the risk-free interest rate (free money - tbills for example), and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is the volatility of the stock.
\end_layout

